            {
              "id": "datadog/java-weakrandomness",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of weak randomness"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Java, Weak Randomness (CWE-330) occurs when java.util.Random or Math.random() is used to generate\ninput for security-sensitive operations like tokens, passwords, session IDs, or cryptographic keys.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```java\nRandom rand = new Random();\nString token = String.valueOf(rand.nextLong());\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use java.security.SecureRandom for security-sensitive random generation.\n- java.util.Random is acceptable for non-security purposes (shuffling, tests, simulations).\n- Never seed SecureRandom with predictable values."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:330",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
