            {
              "id": "datadog/python-brokencrypto",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential use of broken cryptography"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Python, Broken Cryptography (CWE-327) occurs when weak algorithms, modes, or key management\npractices are used to encrypt sensitive input.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```python\ncipher = DES.new(key, DES.MODE_CBC, iv)  # DES is weak\ncipher = AES.new(key, AES.MODE_ECB)  # ECB mode is weak\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use AES with GCM mode or Fernet for encryption.\n- Use secrets module or os.urandom() for random generation.\n- Never hardcode keys or use static IVs."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:327",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/python-cmdi",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential command injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Python, Command Injection (CWE-77) occurs when untrusted input is passed to system commands\n(e.g., os.system, subprocess) via string concatenation or shell=True, allowing arbitrary command execution.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```python\nos.system(\"cat \" + filename)\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Use subprocess with argument lists and shell=False:\n```python\nsubprocess.run([\"cat\", filename], shell=False)\n```\n- Validate/allowlist inputs; avoid passing raw user data to the shell.\n- Prefer Python standard libraries instead of shell commands where possible."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:78",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/python-codei",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential code injection"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Python, Code Injection (CWE-94) occurs when untrusted input is passed to eval(), exec(),\nor used in template string construction.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```python\nexpression = request.args.get(\"expr\")\nresult = eval(expression)\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Never use eval() or exec() with user input.\n- Use ast.literal_eval() for safe literal evaluation.\n- Use pre-defined templates; never construct template strings from user input."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
                  "DATADOG_RULE_TYPE:datadog-ai-static-analyzer",
                  "CWE:94",
                  "SEVERITY:WARNING",
                  "CATEGORY:SECURITY"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "datadog/python-deserialization",
              "shortDescription": {
                "text": "Potential insecure deserialization"
              },
              "fullDescription": {
                "text": "In Python, Insecure Deserialization (CWE-502) occurs when untrusted input is deserialized\nusing pickle, allowing arbitrary code execution.\n\nFor example (vulnerable):\n```python\ndata = request.get_data()\nobj = pickle.loads(data)  # Remote code execution!\n```\n\n## How to remediate:\n- Never use pickle with untrusted data.\n- Use json.loads() which is safe from code execution.\n- Use yaml.safe_load() instead of yaml.load()."
              },
              "properties": {
                "tags": [
